Problem and Requirement Description: ¶

The task is to analyze the clinical and financial data of patients hospitalized for a certain condition. Some variable names and patient_id's have been anonymized in this dataset. It is required to join the data given in different tables, and find insights about the drivers of cost of care.¶

In [157]:
new2_join_bill = join_bill.groupby(["patient_id","date_of_admission"])
new2_join_bill = new2_join_bill["amount"].sum()
new2_join_bill = new2_join_bill.reset_index(name="amount")
new2_join_bill["date_of_admission"] = pd.to_datetime(new2_join_bill["date_of_admission"])

Here we can find that after grouping by patient_id and date_of_admission, the total dataset's row number becomes 3400 rather than 13600, which verifies my assumption that each patient paid bills for more than once in the same day and some patients went to hospital for more than once in different dates.¶

6. Predict cost of care for new patients using regression models¶

Separate original dataset to 3000 train data and 400 test data.¶

In [191]:

Using lasso model, if sum all the medical_history and preop_medication, r2_score_lasso is 0.6708499774248937. When keeping all original columns, r2_score_lasso_train is 0.7191026753830152 and r2_score_lasso_test is 0.7109696896803541. Using general linear regression model, r2_score_linear_train is 0.7211489232349266 and r2_score_linear_test is 0.7105975322040465. So there is no overfitting and the highest r2_score is around 0.71.¶

These regression models can help us predict new cost of care by inputing new patients' features and they can be applied to many fields such as insurance and medical consulting industry. As when we know a patient's personal information we can evaluate their potential cost in health care and insurance company can calculate their risks of selling insurance to those patients. Also those who want to sell special medicine or health equipments can have a better population target.¶
